&gt; &gt; If your tests are dependant from each other, you may reconsider refactor
&gt; &gt; them so that they can be execution in any order.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; As for JUnit, unless you modify the runners, I don&#39;t think you can
&gt; &gt; parametrize JUnit to do what you want.  If you use Ant, you have the
&gt; &gt; &quot;haltonfailure&quot; option of the JUnit task but you have to check if it&#39;s
&gt; &gt; really what you want.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; general note: if you don&#39;t specify a suite() method, JUnit will
&gt; &gt; automatically extract all your test methods from your class.  So you
&gt; &gt; don&#39;t need to write
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;     public static Test suite() {
&gt; &gt;        return new TestSuite(myClass.class);
